            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this heat transfer calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool combines the three classical modes of heat
                transfer—conduction, convection, and radiation—into a single
                interface. It is designed for students, engineers, and hobbyists
                who want quick, reliable estimates with clear formulas.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Conduction (Fourier’s law)</h3>
              <p>
                Conduction describes heat flow through solids or stationary
                fluids due to a temperature gradient. For a single homogeneous
                layer:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\[ Q = \frac{k A (T_\text{hot} - T_\text{cold})}{L} \]</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(Q\): heat transfer rate [W]</li>
                  <li>\(k\): thermal conductivity [W/m·K]</li>
                  <li>\(A\): area normal to heat flow [m²]</li>
                  <li>\(L\): thickness [m]</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <p>
                For multiple layers in series (e.g., plaster + brick +
                insulation), the total thermal resistance is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ R_\text{tot} = \sum_i \frac{L_i}{k_i A}, \quad Q =
                  \frac{\Delta T}{R_\text{tot}}, \quad U = \frac{1}{R_\text{tot}
                  A} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The conduction tab lets you add layers, computes
                \(R_\text{tot}\), and solves either for \(Q\) or for the
                required area \(A\) to achieve a target heat flow.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Convection (Newton’s law of cooling)</h3>
              <p>
                Convection occurs when a fluid (air, water, oil) moves over a
                surface, carrying heat away or toward it. The basic relation is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\[ Q = h A (T_\text{surface} - T_\text{fluid}) \]</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(h\): convective heat transfer coefficient [W/m²·K]</li>
                  <li>
                    \(T_\text{surface}\), \(T_\text{fluid}\): surface and bulk
                    fluid temperatures
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <p>The convection tab can solve for:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Q</strong> given \(h\), \(A\), and temperatures</li>
                <li><strong>A</strong> needed to dissipate a given \(Q\)</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>h</strong> required to achieve a target \(Q\) with a
                  given area
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Radiation (Stefan–Boltzmann law)</h3>
              <p>
                Thermal radiation is electromagnetic energy emitted by bodies
                due to their temperature. For a surface exchanging heat with
                large surroundings:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ Q = \varepsilon \sigma A \left( T_\text{surface}^4 -
                  T_\text{surroundings}^4 \right) \]
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(\varepsilon\): emissivity (0–1)</li>
                  <li>
                    \(\sigma = 5.670374419 \times 10^{-8}\
                    \text{W/m}^2\text{·K}^4\)
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <p>
                The radiation tab computes net radiative heat flux and total
                heat transfer, or the area required to radiate a specified
                power.
              </p>

              <h3>Unit handling</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Temperatures can be entered in °C or K. The calculator
                  converts to kelvin internally; only differences matter for
                  conduction and convection.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Areas can be entered in m², ft², or cm² and are converted to
                  m².
                </li>
                <li>
                  Convective coefficients can be entered in W/m²·K or
                  Btu/hr·ft²·°F.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Typical values and quick checks</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Thermal conductivity k</strong>: ~0.03–0.04
                  (insulation), ~0.7 (brick), ~200 (aluminum) W/m·K.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Convective h</strong>: 5–25 (natural convection air),
                  50–1000 (forced air), 500–10000 (water).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Emissivity ε</strong>: 0.9–0.98 (matte paint), 0.1–0.3
                  (polished metals).
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

